@akien-mga 
the issue you mentioned on irc I dint see because of poor testing ...
@neikeq thank you for sotting it!

It looks like there are vec2, vec3, and vec4 versions of most of the built in functions in the 3.0 shading language, but not for any of the trig functions:

https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1hBpkNor5-WUTKuiEP3Myo4wzleCWvqPqn1OLgOwFsmU/edit#gid=1952867603

Would make porting GLSL code easier. For example [this tutorial](https://thebookofshaders.com/12/) on
cell noise has a random function that uses a vec2 sin():

```
vec2 random2( vec2 p ) {
    return fract(sin(vec2(dot(p,vec2(127.1,311.7)),dot(p,vec2(269.5,183.3))))*43758.5453);
}
```

**Operating system or device, Godot version, GPU Model and driver (if graphics related):**
Windows 7, Godot 3 alpha 1, GTX 770, Driver version 378.49

**Issue description:**
Attempting to use a for loop in a shader:
```
shader_type canvas_item;

void fragment() {
	for (i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
		
	}
}
```

Gives the error: `error(4): Expected expression, found: CF_FOR`

Unsure if I'm doing something wrong, if this is a bug, or for loops just aren't implemented yet?
